Free trade enthusiasts
From Cambridge — recently I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them warned me beforehand: "These students are strong supporters of globalization."
He asked the students present in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90 percent supported the former.
And they were still strong supporters of globalization before the magical effects of comparative advantage had even been introduced.
We know that in real surveys, asking a representative sample — — not Harvard students — — the same question would yield a completely different result.
The ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions in the United States is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not seem particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their own (financial) futures and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they actually do not understand how trade works.
Indeed, when I met with them, I deliberately used a different phrasing to ask the same question and emphasized the potential distributional effects of trade.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared completely, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked the audience whether they agreed with my special magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear — "Abracadabra" — while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account, and the great work of social engineering could add an additional $100 value to the class as a whole.
Would they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.
It is clear that students could not tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even when the overall economic pie had been expanded.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, when free trade would also lead to a similar — in fact, even more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students seemed to be stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John each started a small competing company.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, so he not only ended up with $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing Nicholas to lose $200.
How many students supported this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then introduced another assumption directly related to international trade.
If John had driven Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet well established?
Or employing child labor in Indonesia?
The level of agreement with the shift decreased in the order of the above options.
In addition, technological innovation can also place certain groups in a more vulnerable position, just like trade; what is your stance on this?
Only a few students were willing to restrain technological development.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs to protect the candlemaker's job is simply a foolish idea.
Therefore, what students oppose is not necessarily redistribution itself, but rather certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the outcome of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produced such results.
We do not resent the immense wealth of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett, even though some of their opponents have always struggled, probably because they and their competitors all operate under the same basic rules and face extremely similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy through fraud, breaking labor laws, damaging the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved by violating moral standards generally observed domestically, on what grounds can we feel at ease with it merely because it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to achieve equality in the long run and believe that everyone will ultimately benefit, we are likely not to care about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative consequences for some people, we still choose to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group—low-educated blue-collar workers—we become anxious about globalization.
However, many economists have ignored these obvious distinctions.
They tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to silly and selfish protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they are unable to recognize that international trade sometimes—though not often—leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to appropriately engage in public discourse.
And since they themselves are morally indefensible, how can they defend trade vigorously?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons that require difficult trade-offs, including the possibility that globalization may cause wealth deprivation more severe than that experienced by victims within the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions based on it.
And the practice of being overly enamored with globalization simply because it enlarges the cake will inevitably erode its legitimacy in the long run.
